(1, 'If A+B+C= $ \\pi $, then sin<sup>2</sup>A+sin<sup>2</sup>B+sin<sup>2</sup>C=', '$ 4 \\cos \\dfrac{A}{2} \\cos \\dfrac{B}{2} \\cos \\dfrac{C}{2} $', '2 + $ 2 \\cos A \\cos B \\cos C $', '1 + $4 \\sin \\dfrac{A}{2} \\sin \\dfrac{B}{2} \\sin \\dfrac{C}{2} $', '$ 4 \\sin A \\sin B \\sin C $', 'b', 'Given, A+B+C= $ \\pi $ . S0, let A=B=C= $ 60^\\circ $, then </br>\r\n<br>Question:  sin<sup>2</sup>A+sin<sup>2</sup>B+sin<sup>2</sup>C= 3sin<sup>2</sup>A= $ 3 \\times {\\sin}^2 60^\\circ $ = $ \\dfrac{9}{4} $ </br>\r\n<br> Check all the option for this value. </br>\r\n<br> a) $ 4 \\cos \\dfrac{A}{2} \\cos \\dfrac{B}{2} \\cos \\dfrac{C}{2} $ = $ 4 ( \\cos \\dfrac{A}{2} )^3 $ = $ 4 \\times ( \\cos 30^\\circ ) ^3 = \\dfrac{3 \\sqrt{3}}{2} $ </br>\r\n<br> b) 2 + $ 2 \\cos A \\cos B \\cos C $ = 2 + $ 2( \\cos A )^3 $ = 2 + $ 2 ( \\cos 60^\\circ) $ = $ \\dfrac{9}{4} $  You got your answer. But in subtitution method as this always check all option. Answer may be in more than one place. </br>\r\n<br> c) 1 + $4 \\sin \\dfrac{A}{2} \\sin \\dfrac{B}{2} \\sin \\dfrac{C}{2} $ = 1 + $ 4 ( \\sin 30^\\circ )^3 $ = $ \\dfrac{3}{2} $\r\n<br> d) $ 4 \\sin A \\sin B \\sin C $ = 4 $ ( sin 60^\\circ ) ^3 = \\dfrac{3 \\sqrt{3}}{2} $ </br>\r\n<br> Here, only option b matches the question value. So, option b is the correct answer.', 0),
(2, 'The value of $ {\\cos}^2 \\dfrac{A}{2}+{\\cos}^2 \\dfrac{B}{2}+{\\cos}^2 \\dfrac{C}{2}+ $ =', '1 + $ \\dfrac{r}{R} $', '2 + $ \\dfrac{r}{2R} $', '2 + $ \\dfrac{2r}{R} $', '2 + $ \\dfrac{r}{R} $', 'b', 'Assume, A=B=C= 4cm or some others values as you wish. Better take 3 differnt prime numbers like A=2; B=3; C=5. </br>\r\n<br> Get required values like r, R and the values that you required to have these values. </br>\r\n<br> $ \\Delta = \\dfrac{ \\sqrt{3}} {4} \\times (side)^2 = \\dfrac{ \\sqrt{3}} {4} \\times 4^2 = 4 \\sqrt{3} $ </br>\r\n<br> S = $ \\dfrac{a+b+c}{2} $ = 6 </br>\r\n<br> r = $ \\dfrac{ \\Delta }{s} = \\dfrac{2}{ \\sqrt{3}} $ </br>\r\n<br> R = $ \\dfrac {abc}{4 \\Delta } = \\dfrac { 4 \\times 4 \\times 4 }{4 \\times 4 \\sqrt{3} } = \\dfrac {4}{ \\sqrt{3}} $ </br>\r\n<br> It is better to remember these values do you don''t have to derive them everytime for similar questions. </br>\r\n<br> Question: $ { \\cos }^2 \\dfrac{A}{2}+{ \\cos }^2 \\dfrac{B}{2}+{ \\cos }^2 \\dfrac{C}{2}+ $ = 3 $ { \\cos }^2 \\dfrac{A}{2} = 3 { \\cos }^2 30 $ = 2.25 </br>\r\n<br> a)  1 + $ \\dfrac{r}{R} $ =  1 + $ \\dfrac{1}{2} $ = $ \\dfrac {3}{2} $ <br>\r\n<br> b) 2 + $ \\dfrac{r}{2R} $ =  2 + $ \\dfrac{ \\dfrac{2}{ \\sqrt{3}}}{2 \\times \\dfrac {4}{ \\sqrt{3}}} $ = 2.25</br>\r\n<br> c) 2 + $ \\dfrac{2r}{R} $ = 2 + $ \\dfrac{2 \\times \\dfrac{2}{ \\sqrt{3}} }{ \\dfrac {4}{ \\sqrt{3}}} = 3 $ </br>\r\n<br> d) 2 + $ \\dfrac{r}{R} $ = 2 + $ \\dfrac{1}{2} $= $ \\dfrac {5}{2} $ </br>\r\n<br> Hence, required answer is b.', 0),
(3, 'In $ \\Delta $ ABC, the value of a (bcosC - ccosB) is', 'a<sup>2</sup>-b<sup>2</sup>', '(a - b)', '4a<sup>2</sup>b<sup>2</sup>c<sup>2</sup>', 'b<sup>2</sup>-c<sup>2</sup>  </br>', 'd', 'Here, we cannot consider a equilateral triangle because if a=b=c then a(bcosC - ccosB) = 0. Also, option a,b,d will equal 0.\r\nSo, assume such triangle that will not have a=b=c. Let suppose a triangle ABC such that a=1, b= $ \\sqrt{2} $ , c=1. Then, </br>\r\n<br>a(bcosC-ccosB)= $ ( \\sqrt{2} \\times \\dfrac{1}{ \\sqrt{2} } -1 \\times 0 ) $ = 1. </br>\r\n<br> a) 1<sup>2</sup> -2 = -1 </br>\r\n<br> b) 1 - $ \\sqrt{2} $ </br>\r\n<br> c) 4*1*2*1=8 </br>\r\n<br> d) 2-1 =1 </br>\r\n<br> Hence, correct answer is option d.', 0),
(4, 'The value of $ \\dfrac{1}{ab} + \\dfrac{1}{bc} + \\dfrac{1}{ca} $ =', '$ \\dfrac{1}{2Rr} $', '$ \\dfrac{1}{2rs} $', '$ \\dfrac{1}{2Rs} $', '$ \\dfrac{1}{2R} $', 'a', 'Put a=b=c=4 then </br>\r\n<br> Get required values like r, R and the values that you required to have these values. </br>\r\n<br> $ \\Delta = \\dfrac{ \\sqrt{3}} {4} \\times (side)^2 = \\dfrac{ \\sqrt{3}} {4} \\times 4^2 = 4 \\sqrt{3} $ </br>\r\n<br> S = $ \\dfrac{a+b+c}{2} $ = 6 </br>\r\n<br> r = $ \\dfrac{ \\Delta }{s} = \\dfrac{2}{ \\sqrt{3}} $ </br>\r\n<br> R = $ \\dfrac {abc}{4 \\Delta } = \\dfrac { 4 \\times 4 \\times 4 }{4 \\times 4 \\sqrt{3} } = \\dfrac {4}{ \\sqrt{3}} $ </br>\r\n<br> Now, question = $ \\dfrac{1}{ab} + \\dfrac{1}{bc} + \\dfrac{1}{ca} $ = $ \\dfrac{3}{a^2} = \\dfrac{3}{16} $ </br>\r\n<br> a. $ \\dfrac{1}{2 \\times \\dfrac{4}{ \\sqrt{3} } \\times \\dfrac{2}{ \\sqrt {3} } } = \\dfrac{3}{16} $ </br>\r\n<br> b. $ \\dfrac{1}{2 \\times \\dfrac{2}{ \\sqrt{3} } \\times 6 } = \\dfrac { \\sqrt {3} } {36} $ </br>\r\n<br> c. $ \\dfrac{1}{2 \\times \\dfrac{4}{ \\sqrt{3} } \\times 6 } = \\dfrac { \\sqrt {3} } {54} $ </br>\r\n<br> d. $ \\dfrac{1}{ 2 \\times \\dfrac{4}{ \\sqrt{3} } } = \\dfrac { \\sqrt {3} } {8} $ </br>\r\n<br> Hence, correct option is option a.', 0),
